# Knowledge Base Conventions

## Location

The Knowledge Base lives at `~/.cursor/docs/knowledge-base/`. This is an Obsidian-compatible vault containing generated structural documentation for all projects.

**KB-side only.** All KB write surface — including `.meta/manifest.json`, `.meta/identity.json`, `.meta/generation-log.json` — lives under `~/.cursor/docs/knowledge-base/projects/<name>/`. `kb-engineer` never writes anything into the target project's working tree. `git status` on a project after a KB generation run shows no KB-related file additions.

```
~/.cursor/docs/knowledge-base/
├── Home.md                          # Vault home page, project index
├── _schema/                         # Cross-project validation schemas
│   ├── frontmatter.schema.json
│   ├── graph.schema.json
│   └── manifest.schema.json
├── templates/                       # Document templates
└── projects/
    └── <project-name>/              # Per-project documentation
        ├── README.md                # Project overview
        ├── architecture.md          # Architecture with mermaid diagrams
        ├── dependencies.md          # Dependency inventory
        ├── modules/                  # Per-module documentation
        │   ├── _index.md
        │   └── <module>.md
        ├── services/                 # Per-service documentation
        │   ├── _index.md
        │   └── <service>.md
        ├── graph.json               # Machine-readable relationship graph
        └── .meta/                   # Generation metadata
            ├── manifest.json        # File hashes for incremental updates
            ├── identity.json        # Project identity
            └── generation-log.json  # Generation stats
```

## Document Types

| Type | File | Purpose |
|------|------|---------|
| `overview` | `README.md` | Project entry point, tech stack, quick stats |
| `architecture` | `architecture.md` | System design with mermaid diagrams |
| `module` | `modules/<name>.md` | Module internals, APIs, relationships |
| `service` | `services/<name>.md` | Service boundaries, protocols, dependencies |
| `dependency` | `dependencies.md` | External dependency inventory |

## Frontmatter Schema

Every KB document has YAML frontmatter:

```yaml
---
title: "Module: auth"
type: module
project: myapp
tags: [myapp, module, auth]
generated_at: 2026-04-14T10:00:00Z
generated_by: kb-engineer
source_files: ["src/auth/**"]
confidence: high
stale: false
aliases: ["authentication"]
---
```

See `_schema/frontmatter.schema.json` for full validation schema.

## Diagram Convention

**All diagrams MUST be mermaid code blocks.** No images, no external diagram tools.

| Document | Diagram Type | Mermaid Syntax |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| `architecture.md` | System overview | `flowchart TD` or `C4Context` |
| `architecture.md` | Component diagram | `flowchart LR` with subgraphs |
| `dependencies.md` | Dependency graph | `flowchart LR` with external nodes |
| `modules/<name>.md` | Module internals | `flowchart TD` for call flows |
| `services/<name>.md` | Service interactions | `sequenceDiagram` for API flows |

Obsidian renders mermaid natively. Diagrams are version-controlled as text.

## Agent Responsibilities

| Agent | KB Interaction |
|-------|----------------|
| `kb-engineer` | **Sole writer** to `~/.cursor/docs/knowledge-base/projects/`. Generates, updates, maintains KB docs. |
| `vp-onboarding` | Invokes `kb-engineer` during project bootstrap. |
| `tech-lead` | Queries KB for project understanding. Requests KB refresh after significant changes. |
| `dev-*`, `sme-*` | Read KB via `kb-query` skill. Do NOT write to KB. |

## Three-Tier Documentation Model

| Tier | Location | Content | Ownership |
|------|----------|---------|-----------|
| **Memory** | `~/.cursor/memory/` | Decisions, constraints, risks, principles | Any agent via `context-memory` skill |
| **Project Docs** | `<project>/.cursor/docs/` | Plans, ADRs, runbooks | Agents write, optionally git-tracked |
| **Knowledge Base** | `~/.cursor/docs/knowledge-base/projects/<name>/` | Generated structural docs | `kb-engineer` only |

**When to use which:**
- Memory: Conclusions, "why we decided X"
- Project Docs: "How to do Y", detailed plans
- Knowledge Base: "What this project IS" — structure, relationships, architecture

## Querying the KB

Use the `kb-query` skill with token-efficient tiers:

| Query Need                                       | Method             | Token Cost |
|--------------------------------------------------|--------------------|------------|
| "What is this project?"                          | Level 0            | ~50        |
| "What does this project do?"                     | Level 1            | ~200       |
| "What modules exist?"                            | Level 1            | ~150       |
| "What services exist and how do they talk?"      | `service-topology` | ~200       |
| "How does module X work?"                        | Level 2            | ~500       |
| "How does service X work?"                       | Level 2 (service)  | ~500       |
| "What depends on module X?"                      | Level 3            | ~300       |

## Staleness Handling

- KB docs have a `stale` flag in frontmatter
- `.meta/identity.json` has `needs_refresh` flag
- `kb-query` skill warns when returning stale content
- `vp-onboarding` triggers refresh on re-runs
- **Generator drift** — on every `incremental` run, `kb-engineer` compares `.meta/manifest.json.generator` (agent / skill / template / schema versions + template hashes) against current runtime versions and fills gaps: missing required docs, missing per-entity docs, schema drift, template drift, skill drift, agent-version drift. Gap-fill is additive and idempotent.
